  <data key="d14">ann.concept-simony-misuses-sacred-object-concept-spiritual-thing-st-ii-ii-q100-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q100.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( I-II:18:2 ) an act is evil generically when it bears on undue matter . Now a spiritual thing is undue matter for buying and selling for three reasons. First, because a spiritual thing cannot be appraised at any earthly price, even as it is said concern</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.simony" target="concept.religion" id="edge.concept.simony.deficiency_opposed_to.concept.religion">
  <data key="d6">edge.concept.simony.deficiency_opposed_to.concept.religion</data>
  <data key="d7">concept.simony</data>
  <data key="d8">Simony</data>
  <data key="d9">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d10">deficiency_opposed_to</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.religion</data>
  <data key="d12">Religion</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.concept-simony-deficiency-opposed-to-concept-religion-st-ii-ii-q100-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q100.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">by buying or selling a spiritual thing, a man treats God and divine things with irreverence, and consequently commits a sin of irreligion.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
</edge>
