  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q083.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">According to Cassiodorus [Comment. in Psalm 38:13 " prayer [oratio] is spoken reason [oris ratio]." Now the speculative and practical reason differ in this, that the speculative merely apprehends its object, whereas the </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q083" target="st.ii-ii.q083.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q083</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.83 — Prayer</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q083.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.83 a.2 — Is it fitting to pray to God?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q083.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">Among the ancients there was a threefold error concerning prayer . Some held that human affairs are not ruled by Divine providence ; whence it would follow that it is useless to pray and to worship God at all: of these i</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q083" target="st.ii-ii.q083.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q083</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.83 — Prayer</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q083.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.83 a.3 — Is prayer an act of religion?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q083.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( II-II:81:4 ), it belongs properly to religion to show honor to God , wherefore all those things through which reverence is shown to God , belong to religion. Now man shows reverence to God by means of p</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q083" target="st.ii-ii.q083.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q083</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.83 — Prayer</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q083.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.83 a.4 — Should we pray to God alone?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q083.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">Prayer is offered to a person in two ways: first, as to be fulfilled by him, secondly, as to be obtained through him. On the first way we offer prayer to God alone, since all our prayers ought to be directed to the acqui</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q083" target="st.ii-ii.q083.a005" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q083</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.83 — Prayer</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q083.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.83 a.5 — Should we ask for something definite when we pray?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q083.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">According to Valerius Maximus [Fact. et Dict. Memor. vii, 2, " Socrates deemed that we should ask the immortal gods for nothing else but that they should grant us good things, because they at any rate know what is good f</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q083" target="st.ii-ii.q083.a006" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q083</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.83 — Prayer</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q083.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.83 a.6 — Should we ask for temporal things when we pray?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q083.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">As Augustine says (ad Probam, de orando Deum, Ep. cxxx, 12): "It is lawful to pray for what it is lawful to desire." Now it is lawful to desire temporal things, not indeed principally, by placing our end therein, but as </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q083" target="st.ii-ii.q083.a007" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a007">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a007</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q083</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.83 — Prayer</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q083.a007</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.83 a.7 — Should we pray for others?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q083.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( Article 6 ), when we pray we ought to ask for what we ought to desire. Now we ought to desire good things not only for ourselves, but also for others: for this is essential to the love which we owe to o</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q083" target="st.ii-ii.q083.a008" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a008">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a008</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q083</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.83 — Prayer</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q083.a008</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.83 a.8 — Should we pray for our enemies?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q083.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">To pray for another is an act of charity , as stated above ( Article 7 ). Wherefore we are bound to pray for our enemies in the same manner as we are bound to love them. Now it was explained above in the treatise on char</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q083" target="st.ii-ii.q083.a009" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a009">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a009</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q083</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.83 — Prayer</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q083.a009</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.83 a.9 — The seven petitions of the Lord's Prayer</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q083.a009.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">The Lord's Prayer is most perfect, because, as Augustine says (ad Probam Ep. cxxx, 12), "if we pray rightly and fittingly, we can say nothing else but what is contained in this prayer of our Lord ." For since prayer inte</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q083" target="st.ii-ii.q083.a010" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a010">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a010</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q083</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.83 — Prayer</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q083.a010</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.83 a.10 — Is prayer proper to the rational creature?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q083.a010.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( Article 1 ) prayer is an act of reason , and consists in beseeching a superior; just as command is an act of reason , whereby an inferior is directed to something. Accordingly prayer is properly compete</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q083" target="st.ii-ii.q083.a011" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a011">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a011</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q083</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.83 — Prayer</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q083.a011</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.83 a.11 — Do the saints in heaven pray for us?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q083.a011.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">As Jerome says (Cont. Vigilant. 6), the error of Vigilantius consisted in saying that "while we live, we can pray one for another; but that after we are dead, none of our prayers for others can be heard, seeing that not </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q083" target="st.ii-ii.q083.a012" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a012">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a012</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q083</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.83 — Prayer</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q083.a012</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.83 a.12 — Should prayer be vocal?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q083.a012.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">Prayer is twofold, common and individual . Common prayer is that which is offered to God by the ministers of the Church representing the body of the faithful: wherefore such like prayer should come to the knowledge of th</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q083" target="st.ii-ii.q083.a013" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a013">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q083.contains.st.ii-ii.q083.a013</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q083</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.83 — Prayer</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q083.a013</data>
