<edge source="st.ii-ii.q098" target="concept.perjury" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q098.treated_in.concept.perjury">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q098.treated_in.concept.perjury</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q098</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.98 — Perjury</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.perjury</data>
  <data key="d12">Perjury</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q098-treated-in-concept-perjury-st-ii-ii-q098-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q098.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">Hence falsehood directly annuls the end of an oath : and for this reason, that perversity in swearing, which is called perjury, takes its species chiefly from falsehood. Consequently falsehood is essential to perjury.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q098" target="st.ii-ii.q098.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q098.contains.st.ii-ii.q098.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q098.contains.st.ii-ii.q098.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q098</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.98 — Perjury</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q098.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.98 a.1 — Is falsehood necessary for perjury?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q098.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( II-II:92:2 ), moral acts take their species from their end. Now the end of an oath is the confirmation of a human assertion. To this confirmation falsehood is opposed: since an assertion is confirmed by</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q098" target="st.ii-ii.q098.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q098.contains.st.ii-ii.q098.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q098.contains.st.ii-ii.q098.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q098</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.98 — Perjury</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q098.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.98 a.2 — Is perjury always a sin?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q098.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( II-II:89:1 ), to swear is to call God as witness. Now it is an irreverence to God to call Him to witness to a falsehood, because by so doing one implies either that God ignores the truth or that He is w</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
