  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q098.contains.st.ii-ii.q098.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q098</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.98 — Perjury</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q098.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.98 a.3 — Is it always a mortal sin?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q098.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">According to the teaching of the Philosopher (Poster. i, 2), "that which causes a thing to be such is yet more so." Now we know that an action which is, by reason of its very nature , a venial sin , or even a good action</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q098" target="st.ii-ii.q098.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q098.contains.st.ii-ii.q098.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q098.contains.st.ii-ii.q098.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q098</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.98 — Perjury</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q098.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.98 a.4 — Is it a sin to enjoin an oath on a perjurer?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q098.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">As regards a person who demands an oath from another, a distinction would seem to be necessary . For either he demands the oath on his own account and of his own accord, or he demands it on account of the exigencies of a</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q098.a001" target="concept.perjury" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q098.a001.treated_in.concept.perjury">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q098.a001.treated_in.concept.perjury</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q098.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.98 a.1 — Is falsehood necessary for perjury?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.perjury</data>
  <data key="d12">Perjury</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q098-a001-treated-in-concept-perjury-st-ii-ii-q098-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q098.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Hence falsehood directly annuls the end of an oath : and for this reason, that perversity in swearing, which is called perjury, takes its species chiefly from falsehood. Consequently falsehood is essential to perjury.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q098.a002" target="concept.perjury" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q098.a002.treated_in.concept.perjury">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q098.a002.treated_in.concept.perjury</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q098.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.98 a.2 — Is perjury always a sin?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.perjury</data>
  <data key="d12">Perjury</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q098-a002-treated-in-concept-perjury-st-ii-ii-q098-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q098.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">so doing one implies either that God ignores the truth or that He is willing to bear witness to a falsehood. Therefore perjury is manifestly a sin opposed to religion, to which it belongs to show reverence to God .</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q098.a003" target="concept.perjury" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q098.a003.treated_in.concept.perjury">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q098.a003.treated_in.concept.perjury</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q098.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.98 a.3 — Is it always a mortal sin?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.perjury</data>
  <data key="d12">Perjury</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q098-a003-treated-in-concept-perjury-st-ii-ii-q098-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q098.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">e done out of contempt of God . Wherefore any action that of its nature , implies contempt of God is a mortal sin . Now perjury, of its very nature implies contempt of God , since, as stated above ( Article 2 ), the reason why it is sinful is because it is an act of irreverence towards</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q098.a004" target="concept.perjury" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q098.a004.treated_in.concept.perjury">
