  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q098.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.98 a.4 — Is it a sin to enjoin an oath on a perjurer?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.perjury</data>
  <data key="d12">Perjury</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q098-a004-treated-in-concept-perjury-st-ii-ii-q098-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q098.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">he contrary of what he swears to, "and yet forces him to swear, he is a murderer: for the other destroys himself by his perjury, but it is he who urged the hand of the slayer." If, on the other hand, a man demands an oath as a public person , in accordance with the requirements of the l</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
